SIMPLE: extravagance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Extravagance
<hw>Ex*trav"a*gance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>extravagance</ets>. See <er>Extravagant</er>, and cf.
<er>Extravaganza</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wandering beyond proper
limits; an excursion or sally from the usual way, course, or
limit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being extravagant, wild, or prodigal
beyond bounds of propriety or duty; want of moderation; excess;
especially, undue expenditure of money; void and superfluous expense;
prodigality; <as>as, <ex>extravagance</ex> of anger, love, expression,
imagination, demands</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some verses of my own, Maximin and Almanzor, cry vengeance on me
for their <qex>extravagance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The income of three dukes was enough to supply her
<qex>extravagance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Wildness; irregularity; excess; prodigality;
profusion; waste; lavishness; unreasonableness; recklessness.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 533 --></p>

<p><ent>Extravagancy</ent>⟦br⟧
